---
import Layout from "@halleyfante/documentation/Layout";
import PixCode from "../components/PixCode.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Expressions"
  description="Arithmetic, comparison, and logical expressions in Pix"
  current="expressions"
>
  <p>
    Expressions in Pix define conditions over the coordinate variables
    <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>. They are evaluated for every pixel
    position on the grid to determine which pixels should be drawn.
  </p>

  <h2>Coordinate variables</h2>
  <p>
    <code>x</code> is the horizontal position (increases rightward from 0) and
    <code>y</code> is the vertical position (increases downward from 0). These
    are the only variables available in expressions.
  </p>

  <h2>Operator precedence</h2>
  <p>From lowest to highest:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Precedence</th><th>Operator</th><th>Associativity</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>1 (lowest)</td><td><code>or</code></td><td>Left</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td><code>and</code></td><td>Left</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td><code>not</code></td><td>Unary prefix</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4</td><td><code>=</code> <code>&lt;</code> <code>&gt;</code> <code>&lt;=</code> <code>&gt;=</code></td><td>Binary</td></tr>
      <tr><td>5</td><td><code>+</code> <code>-</code></td><td>Left</td></tr>
      <tr><td>6</td><td><code>*</code> <code>/</code></td><td>Left</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7 (highest)</td><td><code>^</code></td><td>Right</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Arithmetic operators</h2>
  <p>
    These operate on numbers and produce numbers. All arithmetic uses signed
    64-bit integers.
  </p>
  <PixCode code={`x + 5       // addition
x - 8       // subtraction (can produce negative values)
2 * x       // multiplication
x / 2       // integer division (truncates toward zero)
x ^ 2       // exponentiation (right-associative)`} />
  <p>
    Division by zero and negative exponents produce errors.
  </p>

  <h2>Comparison operators</h2>
  <p>
    Comparisons take two numbers and return a boolean.
  </p>
  <PixCode code={`x = 3       // equal
x < 5       // less than
x > 0       // greater than
x <= 5      // less than or equal
x >= 0      // greater than or equal`} />

  <h2>Logical operators</h2>
  <p>
    Logical operators combine boolean values.
  </p>
  <PixCode code={`x = 3 and y = 5           // both must be true
x = 0 or y = 0            // either can be true
not (x = 0)                // negation`} />

  <h2>Parentheses</h2>
  <p>
    Use parentheses to group sub-expressions and override precedence.
  </p>
  <PixCode code={`(x - 8) ^ 2 + (y - 8) ^ 2 < 16   // circle equation
(x > 5 and y < 10) or (x = 0)     // grouped logic`} />

  <h2>Type rules</h2>
  <p>
    Operators require specific types. There is no implicit type coercion.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Operator</th><th>Operand types</th><th>Result type</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>+</code> <code>-</code> <code>*</code> <code>/</code> <code>^</code></td><td>Number, Number</td><td>Number</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>=</code> <code>&lt;</code> <code>&gt;</code> <code>&lt;=</code> <code>&gt;=</code></td><td>Number, Number</td><td>Boolean</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>and</code> <code>or</code></td><td>Boolean, Boolean</td><td>Boolean</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>not</code></td><td>Boolean</td><td>Boolean</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The condition in a <code>draw</code> or <code>erase</code> statement must
    evaluate to a boolean. Using a number expression as a condition produces an
    error.
  </p>
</Layout>
